d with management actions in terrestrial environments, and were incurred through official authorities via monitoring, control or eradication. On natural protected islands, mainly mammals were managed (i.e. rodents, cats and goats), to a total of US$ 3.99 million, while feral cows, fishes and plants were mostly managed in protected mainland areas, amounting to US$ 1.11 million in total.\n              Pterygoplichthys\n              sp. and\n              Eichhornia crassipes\n              caused the greatest reported costs in unprotected aquatic ecosystems in Mexico, and\n              Bemisia tabaci\n              to terrestrial systems. Although reported damages from invasions appeared to be fluctuating through time in Mexico, management spending has been increasing. These estimates, albeit conservative, underline the monetary pressure that invasions put on the Mexican economy, calling for urgent actions alongside comprehensive cost reporting in national states such as Mexico.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Rico-S\u00e1nchez, Axel Eduardo", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Haubrock, Phillip J.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Cuthbert, Ross N.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Angulo, Elena", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Ballesteros-Mejia, Liliana", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "L\u00f3pez-L\u00f3pez, Eugenia", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Duboscq-Carra, Virginia G.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Nu\u00f1ez, Mart\u00edn A.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Diagne, Christophe", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Courchamp, Franck", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Chapter 4", "biodiversity", "environment assessment", "IPBES", "Alien Invasive Species Assessment AIS", "invasive species"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/8b1b3fe96c189e1c699e9f04c4a8b39d", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/133446d58b8a987836a281a6f2a91bae6d31493af2dbcabb8e25f70c150b916b", "relation": "hasVer